"On the whole, non-standard dialect as portrayed on popular television can contribute to stereotyping, although it might sometimes be done more subtley than people might expect," says researcher Jennifer Cramer. Credit: <i>University of Illinois</i> When we talk, our accents and dialects tell others a lot about where we come from and who we are. But popular television often presents people in a way that suggests a connection between their regional speech and their character traits. Jennifer Cramer, an assistant professor of linguistics at the University of Kentucky, is researching how the media represents non-standard dialects of English and what that means for viewers' perceptions of the people who speak them. She is presenting her research today during the Acoustical Society of America's 171st Meeting, being held May 23-27 in Salt Lake City, Utah. Cramer focused on two reality television shows: "The Real Housewives of Atlanta," which features primarily African-American women in Georgia, and "Duck Dynasty," which features a family of self-described "redneck" millionaires in Louisiana. In both shows, she looked at the way that producers subtitled the speech of certain characters. "On the whole, non-standard dialect as portrayed on popular television can contribute to stereotyping, although it might sometimes be done more subtly than people might expect," Cramer said. On "The Real Housewives of Atlanta," she found that producers tended to subtitle words that are part of African American Vernacular English (AAVE), like "finna" (fixing to) or "nair" (narrow). "The subtitles are usually accurate in that they represent what was actually said. However, the choice of what to subtitle is interesting," Cramer said. "The producers are essentially saying 'we think the audience will have trouble with this' or 'we want to highlight the fact that this person is speaking this way.'" On "Duck Dynasty," Cramer noted that the show's producers sometimes used "eye dialect"—nonstandard spelling used to indicate that a character's speech is a non-standard dialect. One example of this is the use of the spelling "gonna" instead of "going to" in a subtitle. "If I say 'gonna,' and the producers write 'gonna,' it's meant to show that I'm speaking in a certain way," Cramer said. "But almost all English speakers say 'gonna' when they're speaking casually. By only using that spelling for certain characters, the producers are making them seem more 'backwoods' or 'uneducated.'" So why does it matter how people are portrayed on TV? Cramer says that it can have real-world consequences for the people who speak these dialects. "When we see these portrayals over and over again, they start to feel like reality," she said. "We begin to associate certain ways of speaking with certain character traits. And that can lead to discrimination in things like hiring or housing." Cramer hopes her research will help people be more aware of the ways that the media can reinforce stereotypes. "The next time you're watching a show and you see subtitles, ask yourself why they're there," she said. "Is it really because the person is hard to understand, or is it because the producers want you to see them in a certain way?" Cramer's research is part of a larger project looking at the linguistic landscape of the American South. She is also studying how people in Kentucky perceive their own and others' dialects. "Our accents are a big part of who we are," she said. "It's important to understand how they're being represented and what that means for our society." Source: University of Illinois <strong>More about:</strong> Linguistics: The scientific study of language and its structure, including the study of morphology, syntax, phonetics, and semantics. Specific branches of linguistics include sociolinguistics, dialectology, psycholinguistics, computational linguistics, historical linguistics, and applied linguistics. Dialect: A particular form of a language that is peculiar to a specific region or social group. African American Vernacular English (AAVE): Also known as Black English Vernacular (BEV), Black English, or Ebonics (a controversial term), AAVE is a variety of English natively spoken, particularly in urban communities, by most working- and middle-class African Americans and some Black Canadians. It has its own unique grammatical, vocabulary, and accent features. Stereotype: A widely held but fixed and oversimplified image or idea of a particular type of person or thing.
